514 Mollia, 6 slack,’ is a natural epithet of sails in a calm, as contrasted with their stiffness when stretched taut by a high wind. The epithet is used by Ovid of a bow that is slack by too much use: see Her. 4, 92 Arcus . . . Si nunquam cesses tendere, mollis erit. For tremunt of flapping sails cf.
